I. Exploratory Data Analysis ¶

Variables Description
TARGET_FLAG Was Car in a crash? 1=YES 0=NO
TARGET_AMT If car was in a crash, what was the cost
AGE Age of Driver
BLUEBOOK Value of Vehicle
CAR_AGE Vehicle Age

CAR_USE Vehicle Use
CLM_FREQ Claims (Past 5 Years)
EDUCATION Max Education Level
HOMEKIDS Children at Home
HOME_VAL Home Value
INCOME Income
JOB Job Category
KIDSDRIV Driving Children
MSTATUS Marital Status
MVR_PTS Motor Vehicle Record Points
OLDCLAIM Total Claims Past 5 Years
PARENT1 Single Parent
RED_CAR A Red Car
REVOKED License Revoked Past 7 Years
SEX Gender
TIF Time in Force
TRAVTIME Distance to Work
URBANICITY Home/Work Area
YOJ Years on Job

I.3 Data Preprocessing ¶

a. Undersampled data ¶

In [12]:
crash = len(train[train.TARGET_FLAG == 1])
no_crash_indices = train[train.TARGET_FLAG == 0].index
np.random.seed(seed=0)
random_indices = np.random.choice(no_crash_indices, crash, replace=False)
crash_indices = train[train.TARGET_FLAG == 1].index
under_sample_indices = np.concatenate([crash_indices, random_indices])
train = train.loc[under_sample_indices]

b. Outliers treatment: sinus transformation ¶

In [13]:
def plot_outliers_transformers(feature):
    feature_val = train[feature]
    feature_sqrt = train[feature].apply(np.sqrt)
    feature_sin = train[feature].apply(np.sin)
    feature_log = train[feature].apply(np.log1p)

    fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=1, ncols=4, figsize=(15, 6))
    sns.boxplot(y=feature_val, ax=axes[0]).set_title(feature)
    sns.boxplot(y=feature_sqrt, ax=axes[1]).set(title=feature+'_sqrt', ylabel='')
    sns.boxplot(y=feature_sin, ax=axes[2]).set(title=feature+'_sin', ylabel='')
    sns.boxplot(y=feature_log, ax=axes[3]).set(title=feature+'_log1p', ylabel='')
    fig.tight_layout()

In [20]:
numeric_transformer = Pipeline(steps=[
    ('imputer', SimpleImputer(strategy='median'))])

categorical_transformer = Pipeline(steps=[
    ('imputer', SimpleImputer(strategy='most_frequent'))])
In [21]:
train_cats_impute = pd.DataFrame(categorical_transformer.fit_transform(X_train[cats_cols]), columns = cats_cols)
train_nums_impute = pd.DataFrame(numeric_transformer.fit_transform(X_train[nums_cols]), columns = nums_cols)
X_train = pd.concat([train_cats_impute, train_nums_impute], axis=1, join='inner')

test_cats_impute = pd.DataFrame(categorical_transformer.transform(X_test[cats_cols]), columns = cats_cols)
test_nums_impute = pd.DataFrame(numeric_transformer.transform(X_test[nums_cols]), columns = nums_cols)
X_test = pd.concat([test_cats_impute, test_nums_impute], axis=1, join='inner')
In [22]:
def encode_one_hot(df, features):
    dummies = pd.get_dummies(df[features])
    res = pd.concat([df, dummies], axis=1)
    res = res.drop(features, axis=1)
    return res

X_train = encode_one_hot(X_train, cats_cols)
X_test = encode_one_hot(X_test, cats_cols)

In [23]:
regex = re.compile(r"\[|\]|<", re.IGNORECASE)
X_train.columns = [regex.sub("_", col) if any(x in str(col) for x in set(('[', ']', '<'))) else col for col in X_train.columns.values]
X_test.columns = [regex.sub("_", col) if any(x in str(col) for x in set(('[', ']', '<'))) else col for col in X_test.columns.values]

II. Modelisation ¶

II.1. Logistic Regression (LogisticRegression) ¶

  • Logistic regression is a linear classification model
  • Score function: $ S(x) = a_1 * x_1 + a_2 * x_2 + \cdots + a_p * x_p $
  • $ P(y = 1|x) = logit(S(x)) = \frac{1}{1 + exp(S(x))} $
    • In [27]:
    lr = LogisticRegression(max_iter=1000) 

cv_score = cross_validate(lr, X_train, y_train, scoring=['accuracy', 'f1_weighted', 'roc_auc'], cv=5)
print(colored('Accuracy: \t', 'blue'), colored(cv_score['test_accuracy'].mean(), 'blue'))
print(colored('F1 score: \t', 'blue'), colored(cv_score['test_f1_weighted'].mean(), 'blue'))
print(colored('Roc auc score: \t', 'blue'), colored(cv_score['test_roc_auc'].mean(), 'blue'))

    II.3. Gradient Boosting (GradientBoostingClassifier) ¶

  • Ensemble learning method for classification
  • Bootstrap aggregating to improve the stability and accuracy
  • Build trees one at a time, where each new tree helps to correct errors made by previously trained tree
    • In [43]:

    III. Tuning model with Gridsearch ¶

    In [55]:
    params = {'learning_rate': [0.1, 0.05, 0.01], 
          'n_estimators':  [100, 200, 300],
          'max_features' : ['sqrt', 'log2']
         }

gb = GradientBoostingClassifier(max_features='sqrt', random_state=0)
gb_grid = GridSearchCV(estimator=gb, param_grid=params, scoring='accuracy', n_jobs=-1, cv=5, verbose=1)
gb_grid.fit(X_train, y_train)
print('Best parameters : ', gb_grid.best_params_)

    Fitting 5 folds for each of 18 candidates, totalling 90 fits
Best parameters :  {'learning_rate': 0.05, 'max_features': 'log2', 'n_estimators': 200}
